reviews.review_text:
Flack at the SPAC
Since this show is AUD-only and from an up-and-down tour, it will mostly appeal to old school '83 fans. Shows had been scheduled here in '72 and then cancelled; now they were back. It's a very uptempo show, but the middling sources suggest that this oddly-shaped, echoey venue was hard to record (those sitting outside the shed looking in were soaked in a downpour). The first set has an energy and tempo that almost belies what is a very flubby batch. The second set is long for the era, at nearly two hours, with one more song than usual after Space plus a double encore. It's this set that once gave the show renown as a trade (well, the Scarlet and the Morning Dew anyway). Bobby has some difficulties this night; Jer a little better, playing mostly off Brent instead, and vice versa. Hellina and Bertha were played at all four SPAC shows, '83-'88. First Set. The Bertha opener is a high energy start, even with some flubbiness. It has "looked over my shoulder" and a wild solo. Jer is in a mood on Jack Straw but Bobby trainwrecks, losing his place and cutting into Jer's solo with the wrong verse. Most copies then cut a technical difficulty section [it can be heard on morrone_119438]. The next few are GOGD; Althea is exciting in places/rough in places. Hellina trainwrecks repeatedly. It's just the third one and still forming (but will still be one of the worst you've heard). Jer leads everyone on Deal, pushing and insisting on leaving 'em happy for the break. It works; it's truly an entertaining Deal. It completely turns around the set and has some unusual dynamics in the jam Second Set. Since most of the show is either flubby or sloppy, the highlights are made more dramatic, and the set starts with one of the trio. In reference to a recess in the weather, Brent starts Scarlet Begonias with the riff from Nash's "I Can See Clearly Now". It continues with superb energy, even if it's not the tightest. And note that, in the jam, Bobby is [unusually] using the same or similar effect as Jer. In Fire on the Mountain, Brent plays another theme (half a minute in), and the band wait for him to finish. It's hard to tell what he's quoting since many songs have this sequence of notes. Fire is mostly average, but third try's a charm on the jams. As it ends, Bobby appends a unique jam, not unlike the chord sequence of Sage & Spirit. Brent joins, Bobby then launches Playing in the Band. At the end of this Bobby again appends. Must hear once. This is not a good Drums>Space, but things improve during the Playing Reprise, in readiness for a great Morning Dew – arguably the year's best. It seems to have made them self-aware, as they come to a full stop momentarily, until Bobby start gathering attentions with Throwing Stones. He has a hard time coalescing this scattered version and it's a slo-mo trainwreck. Not Fade Away puts it back together, but it's a Jenga stack and it falls for Touch of Grey. In this version it's the cows that are running late, and it's Jer's turn to blow lyrics. Dough Knees starts in the wrong key, but Bobby cues Jer, who quickly changes, but then muffs more lyrics. On Saturday Night the band is tired and Bobby's vox are shot. 1st Set:  C 2nd Set: C- Overall = 2¼ stars Highlights: Deal – great dynamics in the jam Scarlet Begonias – superb energy puts it over Morning Dew – so good that they full-stop SOURCES: The 148043_akg_d330bt works the best for me, though no one source is the greatest and it too has issues: the channels are switched on the first set, the beginning of Althea is clipped, and the second set from FotM on is full of dropouts and chewed tape. It's also a bit echoey and has a higher noise floor, making it less dynamic. Better in places is the Jim Wise AUD (gardner_4605 or nawrocki_14411). It has good clarity but runs a little fast, needing -1% pitch correction. It has little stereo image and low volume (better if normalized). It works best for Morning Dew and a couple others, but has a reel flip at the beginning of Touch (a matrix of these two sources might be great – I couldn't get it past the wavering pitches). The wise_miller_103285 is NOT a pitch-corrected Wise AUD, and is not as crisp. The miller_103293 is the once-heavily-traded Silberman AUD. It has a relatively clear 2nd set but no image and is missing the encores. The Keo_124473 is the same source but at slow speed (the Senn441_PCM_Keo runs even slower). The 154660_S2 is the Silberman source EQd and normalized. The miller_105236 is hissy, less dynamic, and slightly fast. The morrone_119438 has the beginning of Dough Knees, that's missing from most sources.
